### Server-Sent Events (SSE)

SSE is simpler than WebSockets when you only need server-to-client messages (notifications, live feeds).

```js
// SSE endpoint for live order status updates
router.get('/orders/:id/status-stream', authenticate, async (req, res) => {
  const { id } = req.params;

  // Verify ownership
  const order = await db.order.findUnique({ where: { id } });
  if (!order || order.userId !== req.user.id) {
    return res.status(403).json({ error: 'Forbidden' });
  }

  // SSE headers
  res.setHeader('Content-Type', 'text/event-stream');
  res.setHeader('Cache-Control', 'no-cache');
  res.setHeader('Connection', 'keep-alive');
  res.setHeader('X-Accel-Buffering', 'no');  // disable Nginx buffering
  res.flushHeaders();

  const sendEvent = (eventName, data) => {
    res.write(`event: ${eventName}\n`);
    res.write(`data: ${JSON.stringify(data)}\n\n`);
  };

  // Send current state immediately
  sendEvent('status', { status: order.status, orderId: id });

  // Subscribe to order updates via EventEmitter or Redis pub/sub
  const handler = (update) => {
    if (update.orderId === id) {
      sendEvent('status', update);
      if (['DELIVERED', 'CANCELLED'].includes(update.status)) {
        res.end();  // close stream when order is terminal
      }
    }
  };

  orderEvents.on('statusUpdate', handler);

  // Heartbeat to keep connection alive through proxies
  const heartbeat = setInterval(() => res.write(':heartbeat\n\n'), 15000);

  req.on('close', () => {
    clearInterval(heartbeat);
    orderEvents.off('statusUpdate', handler);
  });
});
```

### Scaling Socket.io with Redis Pub/Sub

A single Node.js process handles one Socket.io server. When you scale to multiple processes or servers, sockets on different processes cannot communicate directly. Redis Pub/Sub solves this.

```js
const { createAdapter } = require('@socket.io/redis-adapter');
const { createClient } = require('redis');

const pubClient = createClient({ url: process.env.REDIS_URL });
const subClient = pubClient.duplicate();

await Promise.all([pubClient.connect(), subClient.connect()]);
io.adapter(createAdapter(pubClient, subClient));

// Now io.to(roomId).emit() works across all Node.js processes
// The adapter uses Redis PUBLISH/SUBSCRIBE to fan out events
```

### Interview Insight

"How would you scale a Socket.io chat app to handle 1 million concurrent connections?" — One Node.js process can handle ~50,000-100,000 WebSocket connections (memory limited). Scale horizontally with multiple processes/servers, use PM2 cluster mode or Kubernetes pods, add the Redis adapter to share room state across processes, put a load balancer (nginx/HAProxy) with sticky sessions (or IP hash) in front to route reconnections to the same server.

